        "rich_text_rJaBdp": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Introduction",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Vintage jewellery has a certain charm that modern designs sometimes struggle to recreate. When you look closely at an antique-style ring, you’ll often notice delicate details around the edges or on the band. These small touches -tiny bead-like borders, lace-like metal patterns, or hand-carved designs - are what give vintage rings their character.</p><p>Three of the most recognizable techniques used in vintage jewellery are milgrain, filigree, and engraving. While they may look decorative, each of these details reflects a long tradition of craftsmanship that has been used in jewellery making for generations.</p><p>Today, many jewellery lovers are rediscovering these techniques because they add personality and depth to rings. At Lucira Jewelry, vintage-inspired designs such as the Vintage Halo Oval Diamond Ring, Round Solitaire Vintage Engagement Ring, and Regency Bloom Diamond Ring highlight these timeless details while using modern diamonds and materials.</p><p>Let’s take a closer look at what these vintage techniques actually mean.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_A8fUE6": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "What Is Milgrain and Why It Adds a Soft Vintage Edge to Rings",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>What Is Milgrain and Why It Adds a Soft Vintage Edge to Rings</h2>",
            "custom_id": "what-is",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_AJHQPB": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Milgrain is one of the most recognizable elements in vintage jewellery. The word comes from the French phrase <em>“mille-grain,”</em> which means “a thousand grains.”</p><p>In jewellery design, milgrain refers to a row of tiny metal beads placed along the edges of a ring or around a diamond setting. These small dots may look simple, but they create a soft, antique feel that immediately makes a ring look more refined.</p><p>Milgrain details were especially popular during the Edwardian and Art Deco periods, when jewellery makers focused on intricate finishing.</p><p>A ring like the <a href=\"https://www.lucirajewelry.com/collections/solitaire-round\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"Round Solitaire \">Round Solitaire </a>Vintage Engagement Ring often includes milgrain along the edges of the band or around the setting. This small detail frames the diamond and gives the ring a delicate, old-world look.</p><p>Even though milgrain is subtle, it can completely change how a ring feels.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_bhGzpc": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "How Hand Engraving Adds Personal Character to Vintage Rings Engraving is another classic technique t",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>How Hand Engraving Adds Personal Character to Vintage Rings</h2><p>Engraving is another classic technique that gives vintage rings their character. Unlike milgrain or filigree, engraving involves carving patterns directly into the metal surface.</p>",
            "custom_id": "how-hand",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_qwTzXx": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>These designs may include:</p><p>1.] Floral patterns<br/>2.] Geometric shapes<br/>3.] Scrollwork or vines<br/>4.] Personal messages or initials<br/><br/>In the past, engraving was done entirely by hand. Skilled artisans would carve the designs carefully using specialized tools.</p><p>Today, some vintage-inspired rings still feature engraved details to recreate that handcrafted feel.</p><p>For example, a design like the Vintage Halo Oval Diamond Ring often includes subtle engraving on the band that adds depth without distracting from the diamond.</p><p>These details may not be obvious at first glance, but they give the ring personality.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "rich_text_mEE3FU": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "name": "Why These Vintage Techniques Still Matter Today",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<h2>Why These Vintage Techniques Still Matter Today</h2>",
            "custom_id": "why-these",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
        "image_ChqPX3": {
          "type": "image",
          "settings": {}
        },
        "rich_text_NHkmWe": {
          "type": "rich_text",
          "settings": {
            "content": "<p>Milgrain, filigree, and engraving are not just decorative features. They represent the kind of craftsmanship that made antique jewellery so special.</p><p>In earlier times, jewellery was often created slowly by skilled artisans rather than mass-produced. These techniques required patience and attention to detail.</p><p>Today, vintage-inspired designs bring that craftsmanship into modern jewellery.</p><p>Many people are drawn to these details because they make a ring feel more meaningful. Instead of a plain band, the ring carries subtle textures and patterns that tell a story.</p>",
            "custom_id": "",
            "text_alignment": "left"
          }
        },
